accesses.location: Sand boat landing owned by the State of Minnesota on the east side of the lake.

surveys.narrative: Margaret Lake is a designated stream trout lake. The dissolved oxygen and temperature profile were measured in August 2008 and February 2009 to monitor habitat for trout. On August 28, optimal temperature and oxygen conditions for rainbow trout occurred in about 3 vertical ft, from a depth of about 13 ft down to about 15 ft. Adequate oxygen for trout was found down to about 15 ft. In February, oxygen was 4 ppm just under the ice and declined to 1.1 ppm at 25 ft.

Margaret Lake is a designated stream trout lake that is presently managed for rainbow trout. The dissolved oxygen and temperature profiles were measured on August 14, 2013 to monitor habitat for trout. Optimal thermal and oxygen conditions for rainbow trout (11-19 C, > 5 ppm DO) occurred in about 5 vertical ft from about 11 to 15 ft. The TDO3 value was 11.0 C. Margaret Lake will, in some years, have low oxygen in the winter causing winterkill of trout. Despite the sometimes marginal habitat conditions for trout in both late summer and in the winter in Margaret Lake, it appears to be providing a quality trout fishery.

Margaret Lake is a designated stream trout lake that is presently managed for rainbow trout. An assessment of the trout population was made with traps nets in October 2015. Thirty four rainbow trout were captured for an average catch of 6.8 trout per net. The rainbow trout ranged in length from 11.5 to 16.7 inches with a mean length of 13.7 inches and an average weight of nearly one pound. Golden shiners and fathead minnows were the only other species captured.

The dissolved oxygen and temperature profiles were measured on August 12, 2015 to monitor habitat for trout. Optimal thermal and oxygen conditions for rainbow trout (11-19 C, greater than or equal to 5 ppm DO) were not present. The coolest water with DO > 5 ppm was 19.2 C at 15 ft. Margaret Lake will, in some years, have low oxygen in the winter causing winterkill of trout.

Margaret is normally stocked with about 600 yearling rainbow trout each spring. Despite the sometimes marginal habitat conditions for trout in both late summer and in the winter in Margaret Lake, it appears to be providing a quality trout fishery both in open water and the newly opened winter season with fish surviving through the winter in many years.

Designated stream trout lakes have additional angling regulations. Be sure to consult the current Minnesota Fishing Regulations book for regulations, seasons, and possession limits before fishing designated trout waters.

Neither local medians nor quartiles have been developed for lake class 21. Based solely on the statewide medians, the trout population appears high. Age 2 comprised 64% of the trout. One black crappie was captured in the survey, however, no young of year black crappies were captured in the natural reproduction check. Four species of minnows are present.
